snippet.textDisplay: "I'm depressed" then shows chemical nonsense, despite the American Psychiatric Association and the World Psychiatric Association openly declaring the Chemical Imbalance Hypothesis a myth over 15 years ago. And no, they haven't changed their stance. "Chemical Imbalance" is an oversimplified explanation, and what's worse is that people use it to promote the idea that people are "supposed" to be one way instead of another. Epistemologists destroyed teleological theory decades ago, but people are still promoting what they think are optimal concepts without acknowledging the extreme pitfalls in their ideology. By the way the "Chemical Imbalance" hypothesis was a term made up by antipsychiatrists to mock the Amonoamine Hypothesis. The bigger issue is that dumb people like Matpat and Austin appeal to citations that aren't conclusive; they like to adopt crap and say "a paper from X says Z"... as if that were science. It's an appeal to authority, not an appeal to evidence. You can tell neither graduated at the top of their class.

snippet.textDisplay: Cute idea, but, like the "Link is dead in Majora's Mask" nonsense, it's founded on a mere observation that cracks under the pressure of scrutiny. Your conclusion about magic equalling tech is the biggest red flag here: Hyrule has tech, yes, but its magic is hypernatural. Hylians are pagans with a refined polytheism and a history involving reincarnation. The magic Link uses in OoT is more than tech (cf. Din's fire). Clarke was intelligentb but he betrays his pronounced atheism when he dismisses magic as merely a primitive interpretation of future technology.

snippet.textDisplay: You make a good point but I think there are 2 possibilities you overlooked. The first is that Hyrule could take place in the distant past of another planet in our Solar System,  most likely Mars. The Hylians may have used spacecraft to escape to Earth prior to some great calamity that wiped out life on their home planet and humans are descended from this refugees. Alternatively, and I think most plausibly, Hyrule could be a parallel universe version of Earth. It certainly had a history of great technological powers but most of the technology is not at all like our technology, meaning the version of Earth in Hyrule’s parallel universe likely had a different history than Earth since very early on, with just a few things in common in their histories.
